This article seeks to analyse the incorporation of elements from the past in the construction of Jose Sarney’s character right after the launch of the Cruzado Plan. More specifically, how, throughout a discourse related to the memories of the Diretas-Ja movement and of Tancredo Neves, democratic legitimacy has been confered to Jose Sarney, associating him with both. It’s a proccess involvig disputes, generated by contests from the present, in which the past is reviewed and reordered.